troilus and cressida arts at stanford university presented by sica home search this site arts enews subscribe featured archive gallery troilus and cressida stanford drama collaborated with sica and new york's famous the public theater to present william shakespeare's play directed by critically acclaimed director rob melrose both comedic and tragic troilus and cressida tells the story of star crossed lovers during the trojan war troilus a trojan prince falls in love with cressida a prisoner in troy and daughter of a defected trojan priest who resides in the greek camp thus pitting personal and political loyalties against each other in a close resemblance to contemporary conceptions of warfare shakespeare highlights the petty selfish and barbaric preoccupations of disillusioned warriors made worse by their captivity in a drawn out seemingly purposeless war depicts classical heroes ulysses achilles agamemnon hector and others and deals intimately with the timeless debates over peace reputation loyalty and pride stanford drama collaborated with sica and the new york's famous the public theater to present william shakespeare's troilus and cressida directed by critically acclaimed director rob melrose drama department website photo credit michael rooney sica photographer 2009 2010 home calendar gallery news visiting artists grants organizations facilities plan a visit about sica students faculty staff make a gift volunteer login press sitemap contact connect twitter facebook vimeo flickr 2011 stanford university all rights reserved local user login
